  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What does selenium do for the body?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Selenium is an essential trace mineral required for the production of selenoproteins — a family of 25 proteins that serve critical roles in thyroid hormone metabolism, antioxidant defense, and immune function. The thyroid gland contains the highest concentration of selenium per gram of any organ in the body. Selenium is required to convert inactive thyroid hormone (T4) into active thyroid hormone (T3) via the deiodinase enzymes. Without adequate selenium, thyroid function is compromised even if iodine intake is sufficient. Selenium also forms the backbone of glutathione peroxidase, one of the body\'s most important antioxidant enzyme systems, protecting cells from oxidative damage caused by free radicals and reactive oxygen species.' } },
