    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Selenium Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What does selenium do for the body?</summary><p>Selenium is required for 25 selenoproteins that regulate thyroid hormone conversion (T4 to T3), antioxidant defense (glutathione peroxidase), and immune function. The thyroid contains the highest selenium concentration of any organ.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much selenium should I take daily?</summary><p>RDA is 55mcg for adults. Tolerable Upper Limit is 400mcg from all sources. Most gummies provide 100-200mcg. Factor in dietary sources (Brazil nuts, seafood) when choosing your dose.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Which form of selenium is best?</summary><p>Selenomethionine (organic form) has approximately 90% bioavailability and is stored in body proteins. Sodium selenite (inorganic) has 50-60% absorption and is not stored. Selenium yeast naturally contains selenomethionine. Prefer organic forms.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does selenium help with thyroid problems?</summary><p>Yes. Selenium is required for T4-to-T3 conversion and thyroid tissue protection. Clinical trials show 200mcg/day reduces thyroid antibodies (TPO-Ab) by 20-40% in Hashimoto's patients over 3-6 months.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can you take too much selenium?</summary><p>Yes. Selenosis (toxicity) occurs above 400mcg/day total intake. Symptoms: garlic breath, hair loss, nail brittleness, nausea, neurological effects. One Brazil nut contains 70-90mcg. Monitor total intake from food plus supplements.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Who should take selenium supplements?</summary><p>Those with documented deficiency, autoimmune thyroid conditions (Hashimoto's), malabsorption disorders, selenium-depleted soil regions, or dialysis patients. Most Americans get adequate selenium from diet (average 108mcg/day). Test blood levels to confirm need.</p></details>

